\begin_layout Section*
What is digital electronics?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Digital means representing information in discrete whole numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, say you have the four colors, Blue, Green, Red, Yellow.
 To send it digitally, you assign numbers to all the colors, presumably
 as Blue 
\begin_inset Formula $=0$
\end_inset

, Green 
\begin_inset Formula $=1$
\end_inset

, Red 
\begin_inset Formula $=2$
\end_inset

 and Yellow 
\begin_inset Formula $=3$
\end_inset

.
 This is making things digital.
 A digital system uses digits or whole numbers to carry out processes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Why is this needed?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously, to understand and develop the various digital systems that we
 currently have, and possibly for innovations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction to Boolean Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Laws of Ordinary Algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These laws on binary operations are commonly studied in ordinary algebra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Closure Result of a binary operation is in the same set from which the operands
 are.
 It holds for addition and multiplication.
 Examples include 
\begin_inset Formula $2+3=5$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $2\in N$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $3\in N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $5\in N$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Commutativity Result of a binary operation is the same if the order of operands
 is reversed, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y=y+x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

